

Following our one to one, I summarized the key notes regarding our discussion.
After several changes and reorganizations, the team currently lacks a complete, consolidated, and regularly updated list of the work it actually does. As a result, it's not always easy to see the full picture of what the team handles, for some areas of work, the purpose, the intended audience, the specific models or processes involved, who currently owns them, and how they connect to other work, aren't always clearly documented.
As a foundational step, I'd suggest having each sub-team or function identify and organize its own work. The categories below are just illustrative examples to give a sense of the kind of work that might be covered — not an exhaustive list. Each team would be in the best position to identify what actually applies to them:
•	Model-related work — for example, model development, validation support, day-to-day use, ongoing monitoring, and documentation maintenance
•	Reports and other channels of external communication — for example, scheduled and ad-hoc reports, or cross-team forums where the team contributes input rather than producing a formal report
•	Quantitative calculation and analysis work — for example, exposure calculations or methodologies under various regulatory frameworks
•	Ongoing engagement and advisory support — for example, with the front office or other risk teams
•	Regulatory and compliance-related work — for example, items tied to regulators, internal audit, or remediation
•	Internal governance documentation — for example, maintaining SOPs, policies, and procedures
For each item it identifies, a team would capture the same basic set of details: name of the work, its purpose and output, which models or processes it touches, frequency (ongoing, periodic, or ad hoc), current owner, dependencies on other work, and how well it's currently documented. Using a consistent format would also make it easier for each team to keep its own list updated going forward.
The value of this exercise is simple: it gives management a clear, accurate, and easily updatable view of everything the team actually does. Since the team's work will keep evolving — new business, new regulatory requirements, new products — I'd recommend treating this as a living exercise that each team repeats periodically, rather than a one-time effort.

